ot\equiv 0 \ 0 \quad 	ext{ if } a\equiv 0\end{cases} \quad (p)$$ Trial and error I have tried the following potential candidates, but they all fail in at least one of these aspects: Trial 1: $$P( oldsymbol{x}) \stackrel{?}{=} \left(\sum_{i=1}^{p^3} x_i^{p-1}ight)^{p-1}$$ $P( oldsymbol{0}) \equiv 0 \ (p) \quad \checkmark$ But if $ oldsymbol{x} = (\underbrace{1,\dots,1}_p,\underbrace{0,\dots,0}_{p^3-p})$ , then $$P( oldsymbol{x}) = \left(\sum_{i=1}^{p} 1 + \sum_{i=p+1}^{p^3} 0 ight)^{p-1} = p^{p-1} \equiv 0^{p-1} \equiv 0 \quad (p)$$ So in this case, condition 2 fails to hold. Trial 2: $$P( oldsymbol{x}) \stackrel{?}{=} 1-\prod_{i=1}^{p^3} (1-x_i)^{p-1}$$ Clearly holds in this case. $\quad \checkmark$ Also holds, $P( oldsymbol{x}) = 1$ exactly if none of the $x_i$ 's are $0$ , a.k.a., if $ oldsymbol{x} 
e  oldsymbol{0}$ . $\quad \checkmark$ However Condition 3 fails here. The polynomial's degree is $p^3(p-1) = O(p^4)$ . Trial 3: $$P( oldsymbol{x}) \stackrel{?}{=} \left(\sum_{ egin{matrix}I \subseteq \{1,\dots,p^3\} \ |I| = kp \ k \in \{1,\dots,p^2\}\end{matrix}} \left( \sum_{i\in I} x_i^{p-1}  ight)^{p-1}ight)^{p-1} + \left(\sum_{i=1}^{p^3} x_i^{p-1}ight)^{p-1}$$ $P( oldsymbol{0}) \equiv 0 \ (p) \quad \checkmark$ $P( oldsymbol{x}) \equiv 1  \ (p)$ also holds here. The right term is the exact same as the entire polynomial in Trial 1; and the left term equals $1$ for exactly the $ oldsymbol{x}^{p-1}$ 's where number of $1$ 's it contains is divisible by $p$ . $\quad \checkmark$ However $\deg{P} = (p-1)^3 \in O(p^3)$ . (But, we're getting closer. The last example was $O(p^4)$ .) Note: $$P( oldsymbol{x}) \stackrel{?}{=} 1-I( oldsymbol{x} = 0)$$ where $I$ is the real indicator function. However, $P$ needs to be a polynomial , so I can't just use the "regular" indicator function. Context I am trying to prove a theorem using the Chevalley-Warning theorem , which requires certain conditions for the degrees polynomials. The main issue is actually to construct such a polynomial, and once that's done, the theorem would basically "prove itself". However, it is possible, that such a polynomial doesn't exist.

