body_raw:
I'm interested in knowing how, given a set $S$ , one can modify the free group $F(S)$ by adding one or more commutation rules and get a new group. For instance, adding the commutation rule: $$ orall x,y\in S, xy=yx$$ yields the free abelian group generated by the base $S$ . So I'm wondering: does any commutation rule work? For instance, if I say $$ orall x,y\in S, xy=yx^2$$ or even that, for a fixed $z\in S$ , $$ orall y\in S,y
eq z, zy=y^{-1}z^2$$ the first is only possible in the trivial group ( $x=x1=1x^2=x^2$ ) but the second does seem to make sense, at least at a first glance, Which, in general, of these rules produces a new group as compared to those which induce a contradiction or work only in the trivial group? Is there for example a big family of such rules that will tune the original free group into a different, non trivial one? [ Note: I'm not sure what a proper definition of "commutation rule" could be. I just threw some random examples that fit my intuition for such a term.] In particular, take the following example. As a continuation of my previous post ( Extending automorphism to inner automorphism? ), I think I've come to a solution to the following problem. Let $H$ and $K$ be subgroups of a finite group $G$ and assume $H$ is isomorphic to $K$ . Prove that there exists a group $ ar G$ containing $G$ as a subgroup, such that $H$ and $K$ are conjugate in $ ar G$ . (Problem 56 on this problem set .) Let $\phi:H	o K$ be an isomorphism. My idea is to modify the free group in $G\cup\{x\}$ , $F(G\cup\{x\})$ , by letting all the elements of $G$ multiply themselves as usual and by adding the following commutation property. $$ orall h\in H,xh=\phi(h)x$$ Call this new group $ ar G$ . This way, $G\leq ar G$ and for all $h\in H$ , $^xh=\phi(h)$ and in particular $^xH=K$ . [ Note: I know I've added another rule (the one about the elements of $G$ multiplying themselves as usual) but that one could radically be seen as a "commutation property": $ orall g,h\in G, gh=g\cdot_Gh$ .] As I'm not sure if this definition is enough by itself, here's a more schematic definition of $ ar G$ . $$ ar G=\{g_1x^{k_1}g_2x^{k_2}\ldots g_nx^{k_n}:g_i\in G,g_{i>1}
otin H,k_i\in\mathbb{Z},k_{i<n}
eq 0\}$$ Two elements are equal if they have the same canonical form, i.e. the same expression as an interleaved product of elements of $G$ and powers of $x$ , subject of the same conditions that I included in the previous definition. The product of two elements is carried out by concatenating their canonical forms and then commuting all the $g_i$ 's that belong to $H$ , possibly cancelling out some powers of $x$ in the process: since there are only finitely many powers of $x$ in their expressions, this process necessarily ends, yielding the canonical form of their product. Does my "commutation rule" actually generate a new group here? If so, is it a special case or is there a bigger family of "commutation rules" that will produce a group?

